Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Cut the @cauliflower{1%unit} into florets and the stems into pieces.

On a lined #baking tray{}, mix the cauliflower with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Roast on the top shelf of the oven until cauliflower is tender and crispy, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Dilute the @vegetable stock{1%sachet} with @hot water{250%ml} (double for 4p).

Finely chop the @onion{1}(finely chopped).

Peel and grate the @ginger{1%unit}(grated).

Deseed and mince the @chilli{1%unit}(deseeded and minced). Finely chop the @coriander{10%grams}(finely chopped).

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%pack}.

Boil a #pot of salted water for the rice.

Add half the @rice{75%grams} (double for 4p) and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve and pop back in the #pot. Cover with a #lid and leave to the side until ready to serve.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{to taste} in a large pan on high heat.

Fry the onion and chilli (use less if you don't like spice) for ~{2-3%minutes} then add the @North Indian Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} and ginger.

Add the lentils, @coconut milk{180%ml}, and diluted stock to the pan.

Reduce the heat and simmer, covered, ~{10-15%minutes} over medium heat. Add salt and pepper to taste.

Meanwhile, warm the @naan{2%unit} in the oven for ~{4-6%minutes}.

Once the dahl is cooked, just before serving, stir in two-thirds of the roasted cauliflower.

Arrange the rice in deep plates or #bowls{}.

Add the dahl on top, then the rest of the roasted cauliflower.

Sprinkle with the @cashews{10%grams} and coriander.

Serve the naan on the side.